<br />
Originally (and still) mostly set up for board games, they have evolved too and talk about movies, video games and such. It&#39;s kinda cool. I go everyday <br><BR><font size=1>08:43 08-19-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=1">The Founder™</a></B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/magic/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=<a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=1">The Founder™</a>'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">I think if I abstract that - you prioritize accurate game reviews (or at least comprehensive). Neal, knowing what I know about him likes learning things - so if articles are the strong point to Gamerfaqs.com I could understand his choice there. <br />
<br />
I find this subject interesting for a number of reasons. The first reason is because the question "what site (or game, movie, anything really) is the best and why" is a very subjective question. What may be the best for Patrick M. S may not be the best for Neal or me, it could be if we see things alike but it might not be. <br />
<br />
The other reason is because it highlights what I feel is the biggest opportunity for improvement given the now adolescent age of the Internet (well probably more like late childhood). The number of gaming sites out there is pretty ridiculous, just looking at the site you mentioned Patrick the reviews come from 21 to 26 sites. More sites are popping up all the time. <br />
<br />
GamePro&#39;s answer to qualifying a game is to aggregate reviews on a 100 point scale, factoring the reviews of so many professional reviewers seems to insure the review is accurate (ie RottenTomatoes.com). But I find this solution to be simple and unsophisticated, ie. it doesn&#39;t really get to the crux of the problem. <br />
<br />
The third reason is because I think DeckTech.net was miles ahead of the competition, but we unintentionally hitched our wagon to a meteorite and when the card game business tanked so did our appeal. But the data-share concept we came up with originally was really revolutionary for the times. <br />
<br />
Now, the Internet is maturing, and with that maturation comes the problems of qualifying information, sorting our what&#39;s good from what&#39;s not, and frankly the mega sites like google.com and yahoo or bing are not even addressing this question. They are focused on relevance to search paramaters, and popularity. Neither which qualifies information to the point where you can find what you want. <br />
<br />
Anyhow, all that to say if I decide to pursue what I see as an opening I won&#39;t be using card games - more likely video games, or movies, or video game sites, or sites in general. <br />
